{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MubKHfgxqcFQiNueP3KYrs","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Usage\n     2→\n     3→Cloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You write a\n     4→workflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, point Cloche at a project directory, and it\n     5→handles execution, retry logic, and status tracking.\n     6→\n     7→## Prerequisites\n     8→\n     9→- Go 1.25+\n    10→- Docker\n    11→- Git\n    12→- An `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` (for agent steps using Claude Code)\n    13→\n    14→For detailed installation options (pre-built binaries, `go install`, Homebrew,\n    15→Docker-based usage), see [INSTALL.md](INSTALL.md).\n    16→\n    17→## Quick Start\n    18→\n    19→### 1. Build everything\n    20→\n    21→```\n    22→make build\n    23→make docker-build\n    24→```\n    25→\n    26→This produces `bin/cloche`, `bin/cloched`, `bin/cloche-agent`, and the\n    27→`cloche-agent:latest` Docker image.\n    28→\n    29→### 2. Start the daemon\n    30→\n    31→```\n    32→bin/cloched\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→The daemon listens on a Unix socket at `/tmp/cloche.sock` by default. It\n    36→manages Docker containers, tracks run state in SQLite, and handles\n    37→container cleanup. Containers are automatically removed after successful\n    38→runs unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their\n    39→container for debugging.\n    40→\n    41→To enable the web dashboard, set `CLOCHE_HTTP` (e.g.\n    42→`CLOCHE_HTTP=:8080 bin/cloched`). The dashboard is not started unless\n    43→this variable is set.\n    44→\n    45→### 3. Run a workflow\n    46→\n    47→From your project directory (must be inside a git repository):\n    48→\n    49→```\n    50→cd my-project\n    51→cloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add user authentication\"\n    52→```\n    53→\n    54→This will:\n    55→1. Write your prompt to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`\n    56→2. Create a Docker container and copy your entire project into it (no bind mounts)\n    57→3. Apply any override files from `.cloche/overrides/` on top\n    58→4. Start the container, which runs `cloche-agent` to walk the workflow graph\n    59→5. When the workflow finishes, the daemon extracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch\n    60→\n    61→### 4. Monitor progress\n    62→\n    63→```\n    64→cloche status <run-id>\n    65→cloche list\n    66→```\n    67→\n    68→### 5. Get the results\n    69→\n    70→When the run completes, the agent's work is on a git branch:\n    71→\n    72→```\n    73→git branch | grep cloche/\n    74→git diff main..cloche/<run-id>\n    75→```\n    76→\n    77→To merge results into your working branch:\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→git merge cloche/<run-id>\n    81→# or cherry-pick, rebase, etc.\n    82→```\n    83→\n    84→To clean up run branches:\n    85→\n    86→```\n    87→git branch -D cloche/<run-id>\n    88→```\n    89→\n    90→## Container Isolation Model\n    91→\n    92→Cloche provides **total filesystem isolation** between the host and container:\n    93→\n    94→- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the entire project root into the container at\n    95→  `/workspace/`. No bind mounts for project files. Override files from\n    96→  `.cloche/overrides/` are then copied on top (e.g., a container-specific\n    97→  `CLAUDE.md`). The `.git/` directory is included so agents have git context.\n    98→- **Files out**: When the workflow completes, the daemon extracts results from\n    99→  the container via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits them to a\n   100→  `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n   101→- **Auth mounts**: `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` are bind-mounted read-only\n   102→  for Claude Code OAuth session reuse. `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is passed as an\n   103→  environment variable.\n   104→- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n   105→\n   106→Your project directory is never modified by the container. All changes live\n   107→on the run branch until you explicitly merge them.\n   108→\n   109→## CLI Reference\n   110→\n   111→### `cloche init`\n   112→\n   113→Scaffold a new Cloche project in the current directory.\n   114→\n   115→```\n   116→cloche init [--workflow <name>] [--image <base>]\n   117→```\n   118→\n   119→| Flag | Default | Description |\n   120→|------|---------|-------------|\n   121→| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n   122→| `--image <base>` | `ubuntu:24.04` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n   123→\n   124→Creates `.cloche/` with a workflow file, Dockerfile, and prompt templates\n   125→(`implement.md`, `fix.md`, `update-docs.md`). Skips files that already exist.\n   126→Also adds gitignore entries for runtime state directories.\n   127→\n   128→### `cloche health`\n   129→\n   130→Show project health summary based on recent run results.\n   131→\n   132→```\n   133→cloche health\n   134→```\n   135→\n   136→Requires `CLOCHE_HTTP` to be set (e.g. `export CLOCHE_HTTP=localhost:8080`).\n   137→Fetches health data from the daemon's HTTP API (`GET /api/projects`) and\n   138→displays a table with per-project pass/fail counts:\n   139→\n   140→```\n   141→PROJECT          STATUS    PASSED  FAILED  TOTAL\n   142→my-project       green     5       0       5\n   143→other-project    yellow    3       2       5\n   144→```\n   145→\n   146→Status is colored (green/yellow/red) when output is a TTY.\n   147→\n   148→### `cloche run`\n   149→\n   150→Launch a workflow run.\n   151→\n   152→```\n   153→cloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n   154→```\n   155→\n   156→| Flag | Description |\n   157→|------|-------------|\n   158→| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche` in the project directory. |\n   159→| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` and injected into agent steps. |\n   160→| `--keep-container` | Keep the Docker container even on success (default: remove on success). Failed runs always keep their container for debugging. |\n   161→\n   162→The current working directory is used as the project directory. It must be\n   163→inside a git repository (Cloche needs the repo root for result extraction\n   164→via git worktrees).\n   165→\n   166→When starting a run, the daemon checks whether the Docker image is up-to-date\n   167→with the project's `.cloche/Dockerfile`. If the Dockerfile has changed since\n   168→the last build (tracked via a SHA-256 label on the image), the daemon rebuilds\n   169→the image automatically before launching the container.\n   170→\n   171→### `cloche status`\n   172→\n   173→Check the status of a run.\n   174→\n   175→```\n   176→cloche status <run-id>\n   177→```\n   178→\n   179→Output includes the run state, active steps, and per-step results with timestamps.\n   180→\n   181→### `cloche list`\n   182→\n   183→List runs (last hour by default).\n   184→\n   185→```\n   186→cloche list [--all]\n   187→```\n   188→\n   189→| Flag | Description |\n   190→|------|-------------|\n   191→| `--all` | Show all runs, not just the last hour. |\n   192→\n   193→Columns: run ID, workflow name, state, container ID (if running), error message (if failed).\n   194→\n   195→### `cloche logs`\n   196→\n   197→Show logs for a run.\n   198→\n   199→```\n   200→cloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [--follow]\n   201→```\n   202→\n   203→| Flag | Description |\n   204→|------|-------------|\n   205→| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n   206→| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Show only logs of the specified type (`full` = unified log, `script` = script output, `llm` = LLM conversation). |\n   207→| `--follow`, `-f` | Stream live log lines via SSE. Color-coded by type: status (blue), LLM (green), script (default). Exits when the run completes. Connects to the daemon's HTTP endpoint (see `CLOCHE_HTTP` in Client Configuration). |\n   208→\n   209→Without flags, shows the unified log (`full.log`) if available, otherwise streams\n   210→step start/completion events and run results.\n   211→With `--follow`, connects to the SSE endpoint and prints log lines in real-time.\n   212→\n   213→### `cloche poll`\n   214→\n   215→Wait for a run to finish, printing progress updates.\n   216→\n   217→```\n   218→cloche poll <run-id>\n   219→```\n   220→\n   221→Polls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure or if the container\n   222→dies unexpectedly.\n   223→\n   224→### `cloche stop`\n   225→\n   226→Cancel a running workflow.\n   227→\n   228→```\n   229→cloche stop <run-id>\n   230→```\n   231→\n   232→### `cloche delete`\n   233→\n   234→Delete a retained Docker container. Accepts either a Docker container name/ID\n   235→or a Cloche run ID. If given a run ID, the daemon looks up the associated\n   236→container.\n   237→\n   238→```\n   239→cloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n   240→```\n   241→\n   242→### `cloche orchestrate`\n   243→\n   244→Dispatch ready workflow runs for the current project. Checks the project's\n   245→issue tracker for unclaimed tasks, generates prompts, and launches runs.\n   246→\n   247→```\n   248→cloche orchestrate\n   249→```\n   250→\n   251→Uses the current working directory as the project directory. Prints \"No ready\n   252→work found.\" if there are no tasks to dispatch, or \"Dispatched N run(s).\"\n   253→with the count.\n   254→\n   255→### `cloche shutdown`\n   256→\n   257→Shut down the daemon.\n   258→\n   259→```\n   260→cloche shutdown\n   261→```\n   262→\n   263→## Setting Up a New Project\n   264→\n   265→### 1. Scaffold the project\n   266→\n   267→Run `cloche init` from your project root to create the `.cloche/` directory with\n   268→default workflow, Dockerfile, and prompt templates:\n   269→\n   270→```\n   271→cd my-project\n   272→cloche init\n   273→```\n   274→\n   275→Or create the structure manually:\n   276→\n   277→### 2. Create a workflow file\n   278→\n   279→Add `.cloche/<name>.cloche`:\n   280→\n   281→```\n   282→workflow \"develop\" {\n   283→  step implement {\n   284→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n   285→    results = [success, fail]\n   286→  }\n   287→\n   288→  step test {\n   289→    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n   290→    results = [success, fail]\n   291→  }\n   292→\n   293→  step fix {\n   294→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   295→    max_attempts = \"2\"\n   296→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   297→  }\n   298→\n   299→  step update-docs {\n   300→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/update-docs.md\")\n   301→    results = [success, fail]\n   302→  }\n   303→\n   304→  implement:success -> test\n   305→  implement:fail -> abort\n   306→\n   307→  test:success -> update-docs\n   308→  test:fail -> fix\n   309→\n   310→  fix:success -> test\n   311→  fix:fail -> abort\n   312→  fix:give-up -> abort\n   313→\n   314→  update-docs:success -> done\n   315→  update-docs:fail -> done\n   316→}\n   317→```\n   318→\n   319→### 3. Write prompt templates\n   320→\n   321→Create `.cloche/prompts/` with markdown files:\n   322→\n   323→**`.cloche/prompts/implement.md`** — Instructions for the initial implementation:\n   324→```markdown\n   325→You are working on a project. Implement the following change:\n   326→\n   327→## User Request\n   328→(The user prompt is injected automatically by the agent adapter)\n   329→\n   330→## Guidelines\n   331→- Follow existing project conventions\n   332→- Write tests for new functionality\n   333→- Run tests locally before declaring success\n   334→```\n   335→\n   336→**`.cloche/prompts/fix.md`** — Instructions for fixing failures:\n   337→```markdown\n   338→The previous attempt had failures. Review the output logs in .cloche/output/\n   339→and fix the issues.\n   340→\n   341→## Guidelines\n   342→- Read the test/lint output carefully\n   343→- Fix the root cause, not the symptoms\n   344→- Run tests again to verify your fix\n   345→```\n   346→\n   347→**`.cloche/prompts/update-docs.md`** — Instructions for keeping docs in sync:\n   348→```markdown\n   349→Review the CLI source code and update usage documentation to reflect any changes.\n   350→```\n   351→\n   352→### 4. Add overrides (optional)\n   353→\n   354→Files in `.cloche/overrides/` are copied on top of `/workspace/` in the\n   355→container. Use this for container-specific configuration:\n   356→\n   357→```\n   358→.cloche/overrides/\n   359→  CLAUDE.md              # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (replaces host version)\n   360→```\n   361→\n   362→### 5. Make sure your project builds in the container\n   363→\n   364→The default Dockerfile generated by `cloche init` uses `ubuntu:24.04` as its\n   365→base image (configurable via `--image`). If your project needs different\n   366→dependencies, edit `.cloche/Dockerfile`:\n   367→\n   368→```dockerfile\n   369→FROM golang:1.25 AS builder\n   370→WORKDIR /src\n   371→COPY go.mod go.sum ./\n   372→RUN go mod download\n   373→COPY . .\n   374→RUN CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -o /cloche-agent ./cmd/cloche-agent\n   375→\n   376→FROM ubuntu:24.04\n   377→RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y git <your-deps> && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n   378→RUN npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\n   379→COPY --from=builder /cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/cloche-agent\n   380→RUN useradd -m -s /bin/bash agent\n   381→WORKDIR /workspace\n   382→RUN chown agent:agent /workspace\n   383→USER agent\n   384→```\n   385→\n   386→Key requirements for the image:\n   387→- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n   388→- `git` installed (for pushing results back)\n   389→- An `agent` user (cloche wraps the command with `chown` + `su agent`)\n   390→- `/workspace` as the working directory\n   391→- Your project's build dependencies\n   392→\n   393→The daemon automatically rebuilds the image when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes\n   394→(see `cloche run` above). To build manually:\n   395→```\n   396→docker build -t my-project-agent -f .cloche/Dockerfile .\n   397→CLOCHE_IMAGE=my-project-agent:latest bin/cloched\n   398→```\n   399→\n   400→### 6. Run it\n   401→\n   402→```\n   403→cd my-project\n   404→cloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add feature X\"\n   405→```\n   406→\n   407→## Writing Workflows\n   408→\n   409→Workflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in the `.cloche/` directory. See\n   410→[workflows.md](workflows.md) for full DSL reference.\n   411→\n   412→### Step Types\n   413→\n   414→**Agent steps** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent autonomously:\n   415→\n   416→```\n   417→step implement {\n   418→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n   419→  results = [success, fail]\n   420→}\n   421→```\n   422→\n   423→**Script steps** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command:\n   424→\n   425→```\n   426→step test {\n   427→  run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n   428→  results = [success, fail]\n   429→}\n   430→```\n   431→\n   432→### Wiring\n   433→\n   434→Connect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n   435→\n   436→```\n   437→implement:success -> test\n   438→implement:fail -> abort\n   439→test:success -> done\n   440→test:fail -> fix\n   441→```\n   442→\n   443→`done` and `abort` are built-in terminals for success and failure.\n   444→\n   445→### Retry Loops\n   446→\n   447→Wire failures back to earlier steps:\n   448→\n   449→```\n   450→test:fail -> fix\n   451→fix:success -> test    // retry the test\n   452→fix:fail -> abort\n   453→```\n   454→\n   455→### Max Attempts\n   456→\n   457→Limit retries on agent steps. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n   458→\n   459→```\n   460→step fix {\n   461→  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n   462→  max_attempts = \"2\"\n   463→  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   464→}\n   465→```\n   466→\n   467→### Parallel Branches\n   468→\n   469→Wire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n   470→\n   471→```\n   472→test:success -> lint\n   473→test:success -> quality\n   474→```\n   475→\n   476→### Collect (Join)\n   477→\n   478→Synchronize parallel branches:\n   479→\n   480→```\n   481→collect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n   482→```\n   483→\n   484→`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n   485→\n   486→### Agent Command Override\n   487→\n   488→Agent steps use Claude Code by default. Override per-step:\n   489→\n   490→```\n   491→step implement {\n   492→  prompt = \"...\"\n   493→  agent_command = \"aider\"\n   494→  results = [success, fail]\n   495→}\n   496→```\n   497→\n   498→Or at the workflow level via a `container` block:\n   499→\n   500→```\n   501→workflow \"develop\" {\n   502→  container {\n   503→    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n   504→  }\n   505→  ...\n   506→}\n   507→```\n   508→\n   509→Or globally via `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable.\n   510→\n   511→Priority (highest to lowest): step-level `agent_command`, workflow-level\n   512→`container { agent_command }`, `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var, default (`claude`).\n   513→\n   514→### Agent Fallback Chains\n   515→\n   516→Use a comma-separated list in `agent_command` to configure fallback chains. If\n   517→the first agent errors without reporting a result, the system tries the next:\n   518→\n   519→```\n   520→step implement {\n   521→  prompt = \"...\"\n   522→  agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n   523→  results = [success, fail]\n   524→}\n   525→```\n   526→\n   527→Fallback rules:\n   528→- **Command not found or failed to start** — fall back to next command\n   529→- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — fall back to next command\n   530→- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n   531→- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n   532→- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n   533→- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n   534→\n   535→Known agents have default arguments (e.g., Claude gets\n   536→`-p --output-format text --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Other agents receive\n   537→the prompt on stdin with no extra flags. Override with `agent_args` at the step\n   538→or workflow level.\n   539→\n   540→## Result Protocol\n   541→\n   542→Steps report results by writing a marker to stdout:\n   543→\n   544→```\n   545→CLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n   546→```\n   547→\n   548→For script steps, if no marker is written, the exit code determines the result:\n   549→0 = `success`, non-zero = `fail`. Agent steps follow the same convention.\n   550→\n   551→## Prompt Assembly\n   552→\n   553→When an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from multiple sources:\n   554→\n   555→1. The step's `prompt` content (inline or from `file()`)\n   556→2. The user prompt from `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt`)\n   557→3. Validation output from `.cloche/<run-id>/output/*.log` (output from previous script steps)\n   558→4. Result selection instructions listing the step's declared results\n   559→\n   560→## Project Directory Layout\n   561→\n   562→```\n   563→my-project/\n   564→├── .cloche/\n   565→│   ├── develop.cloche        # Workflow definition\n   566→│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image\n   567→│   ├── prompts/\n   568→│   │   ├── implement.md      # Prompt templates\n   569→│   │   ├── fix.md\n   570→│   │   └── update-docs.md\n   571→│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/ in container\n   572→│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n   573→│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n   574→│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt (from --prompt flag)\n   575→│       ├── output/\n   576→│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified chronological log (status + script + LLM)\n   577→│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n   578→│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation output\n   579→│       ├── attempt_count/\n   580→│       │   └── fix           # Retry counter for max_attempts\n   581→│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n   582→├── src/                      # Existing project source (untouched)\n   583→├── CLAUDE.md                 # Host CLAUDE.md\n   584→└── .git/\n   585→```\n   586→\n   587→## Daemon Configuration\n   588→\n   589→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   590→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   591→| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address (unix socket or TCP) |\n   592→| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n   593→| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` (container) or `local` (subprocess, for dev) |\n   594→| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n   595→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | — | HTTP address for the web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n   596→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | (auto-detected) | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n   597→| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | — | Command for LLM calls — evolution and merge conflict resolution (e.g. `claude`) |\n   598→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | — | Passed into Docker containers |\n   599→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | — | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n   600→| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | — | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n   601→\n   602→### Client Configuration\n   603→\n   604→| Variable | Default | Description |\n   605→|----------|---------|-------------|\n   606→| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon address (gRPC) |\n   607→| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address (web dashboard, `cloche logs --follow`) |\n   608→\n   609→## Build Commands\n   610→\n   611→```\n   612→make build          # Build all binaries to bin/\n   613→make test           # Run all tests\n   614→make test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\n   615→make lint           # Run go vet\n   616→make proto          # Regenerate gRPC code from protobuf\n   617→make docker-build   # Build the cloche-agent Docker image\n   618→make install        # Build, install to ~/.local/bin/, restart daemon\n   619→make clean          # Remove bin/\n   620→```\n   621→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f160845f-7287-4e1b-bb4f-9126514fdaa6","uuid":"45ef6f4b-e9bf-4470-b7c9-3d477ac4f9c6","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","content":"# Usage\n\nCloche runs containerized workflows for autonomous coding agents. You write a\nworkflow graph in the `.cloche` DSL, point Cloche at a project directory, and it\nhandles execution, retry logic, and status tracking.\n\n## Prerequisites\n\n- Go 1.25+\n- Docker\n- Git\n- An `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` (for agent steps using Claude Code)\n\nFor detailed installation options (pre-built binaries, `go install`, Homebrew,\nDocker-based usage), see [INSTALL.md](INSTALL.md).\n\n## Quick Start\n\n### 1. Build everything\n\n```\nmake build\nmake docker-build\n```\n\nThis produces `bin/cloche`, `bin/cloched`, `bin/cloche-agent`, and the\n`cloche-agent:latest` Docker image.\n\n### 2. Start the daemon\n\n```\nbin/cloched\n```\n\nThe daemon listens on a Unix socket at `/tmp/cloche.sock` by default. It\nmanages Docker containers, tracks run state in SQLite, and handles\ncontainer cleanup. Containers are automatically removed after successful\nruns unless `--keep-container` is set. Failed runs always keep their\ncontainer for debugging.\n\nTo enable the web dashboard, set `CLOCHE_HTTP` (e.g.\n`CLOCHE_HTTP=:8080 bin/cloched`). The dashboard is not started unless\nthis variable is set.\n\n### 3. Run a workflow\n\nFrom your project directory (must be inside a git repository):\n\n```\ncd my-project\ncloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add user authentication\"\n```\n\nThis will:\n1. Write your prompt to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt`\n2. Create a Docker container and copy your entire project into it (no bind mounts)\n3. Apply any override files from `.cloche/overrides/` on top\n4. Start the container, which runs `cloche-agent` to walk the workflow graph\n5. When the workflow finishes, the daemon extracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` branch\n\n### 4. Monitor progress\n\n```\ncloche status <run-id>\ncloche list\n```\n\n### 5. Get the results\n\nWhen the run completes, the agent's work is on a git branch:\n\n```\ngit branch | grep cloche/\ngit diff main..cloche/<run-id>\n```\n\nTo merge results into your working branch:\n\n```\ngit merge cloche/<run-id>\n# or cherry-pick, rebase, etc.\n```\n\nTo clean up run branches:\n\n```\ngit branch -D cloche/<run-id>\n```\n\n## Container Isolation Model\n\nCloche provides **total filesystem isolation** between the host and container:\n\n- **Files in**: `docker cp` copies the entire project root into the container at\n  `/workspace/`. No bind mounts for project files. Override files from\n  `.cloche/overrides/` are then copied on top (e.g., a container-specific\n  `CLAUDE.md`). The `.git/` directory is included so agents have git context.\n- **Files out**: When the workflow completes, the daemon extracts results from\n  the container via `docker cp` into a git worktree and commits them to a\n  `cloche/<run-id>` branch.\n- **Auth mounts**: `~/.claude` and `~/.claude.json` are bind-mounted read-only\n  for Claude Code OAuth session reuse. `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is passed as an\n  environment variable.\n- **Network**: Containers have network access (needed for API calls).\n\nYour project directory is never modified by the container. All changes live\non the run branch until you explicitly merge them.\n\n## CLI Reference\n\n### `cloche init`\n\nScaffold a new Cloche project in the current directory.\n\n```\ncloche init [--workflow <name>] [--image <base>]\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Description |\n|------|---------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | `develop` | Workflow name. Creates `.cloche/<name>.cloche`. |\n| `--image <base>` | `ubuntu:24.04` | Base Docker image for the generated Dockerfile. |\n\nCreates `.cloche/` with a workflow file, Dockerfile, and prompt templates\n(`implement.md`, `fix.md`, `update-docs.md`). Skips files that already exist.\nAlso adds gitignore entries for runtime state directories.\n\n### `cloche health`\n\nShow project health summary based on recent run results.\n\n```\ncloche health\n```\n\nRequires `CLOCHE_HTTP` to be set (e.g. `export CLOCHE_HTTP=localhost:8080`).\nFetches health data from the daemon's HTTP API (`GET /api/projects`) and\ndisplays a table with per-project pass/fail counts:\n\n```\nPROJECT          STATUS    PASSED  FAILED  TOTAL\nmy-project       green     5       0       5\nother-project    yellow    3       2       5\n```\n\nStatus is colored (green/yellow/red) when output is a TTY.\n\n### `cloche run`\n\nLaunch a workflow run.\n\n```\ncloche run --workflow <name> [--prompt \"...\"] [--keep-container]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--workflow <name>` | Workflow name. Resolves to `.cloche/<name>.cloche` in the project directory. |\n| `--prompt \"...\"`, `-p` | Inline prompt written to `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` and injected into agent steps. |\n| `--keep-container` | Keep the Docker container even on success (default: remove on success). Failed runs always keep their container for debugging. |\n\nThe current working directory is used as the project directory. It must be\ninside a git repository (Cloche needs the repo root for result extraction\nvia git worktrees).\n\nWhen starting a run, the daemon checks whether the Docker image is up-to-date\nwith the project's `.cloche/Dockerfile`. If the Dockerfile has changed since\nthe last build (tracked via a SHA-256 label on the image), the daemon rebuilds\nthe image automatically before launching the container.\n\n### `cloche status`\n\nCheck the status of a run.\n\n```\ncloche status <run-id>\n```\n\nOutput includes the run state, active steps, and per-step results with timestamps.\n\n### `cloche list`\n\nList runs (last hour by default).\n\n```\ncloche list [--all]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--all` | Show all runs, not just the last hour. |\n\nColumns: run ID, workflow name, state, container ID (if running), error message (if failed).\n\n### `cloche logs`\n\nShow logs for a run.\n\n```\ncloche logs <run-id> [--step <name>] [--type <full|script|llm>] [--follow]\n```\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| `--step <name>` | Show only logs for the specified step. |\n| `--type <full\\|script\\|llm>` | Show only logs of the specified type (`full` = unified log, `script` = script output, `llm` = LLM conversation). |\n| `--follow`, `-f` | Stream live log lines via SSE. Color-coded by type: status (blue), LLM (green), script (default). Exits when the run completes. Connects to the daemon's HTTP endpoint (see `CLOCHE_HTTP` in Client Configuration). |\n\nWithout flags, shows the unified log (`full.log`) if available, otherwise streams\nstep start/completion events and run results.\nWith `--follow`, connects to the SSE endpoint and prints log lines in real-time.\n\n### `cloche poll`\n\nWait for a run to finish, printing progress updates.\n\n```\ncloche poll <run-id>\n```\n\nPolls every 2 seconds. Exits 0 on success, 1 on failure or if the container\ndies unexpectedly.\n\n### `cloche stop`\n\nCancel a running workflow.\n\n```\ncloche stop <run-id>\n```\n\n### `cloche delete`\n\nDelete a retained Docker container. Accepts either a Docker container name/ID\nor a Cloche run ID. If given a run ID, the daemon looks up the associated\ncontainer.\n\n```\ncloche delete <container-or-run-id>\n```\n\n### `cloche orchestrate`\n\nDispatch ready workflow runs for the current project. Checks the project's\nissue tracker for unclaimed tasks, generates prompts, and launches runs.\n\n```\ncloche orchestrate\n```\n\nUses the current working directory as the project directory. Prints \"No ready\nwork found.\" if there are no tasks to dispatch, or \"Dispatched N run(s).\"\nwith the count.\n\n### `cloche shutdown`\n\nShut down the daemon.\n\n```\ncloche shutdown\n```\n\n## Setting Up a New Project\n\n### 1. Scaffold the project\n\nRun `cloche init` from your project root to create the `.cloche/` directory with\ndefault workflow, Dockerfile, and prompt templates:\n\n```\ncd my-project\ncloche init\n```\n\nOr create the structure manually:\n\n### 2. Create a workflow file\n\nAdd `.cloche/<name>.cloche`:\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"2\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  step update-docs {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/update-docs.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail -> abort\n\n  test:success -> update-docs\n  test:fail -> fix\n\n  fix:success -> test\n  fix:fail -> abort\n  fix:give-up -> abort\n\n  update-docs:success -> done\n  update-docs:fail -> done\n}\n```\n\n### 3. Write prompt templates\n\nCreate `.cloche/prompts/` with markdown files:\n\n**`.cloche/prompts/implement.md`** — Instructions for the initial implementation:\n```markdown\nYou are working on a project. Implement the following change:\n\n## User Request\n(The user prompt is injected automatically by the agent adapter)\n\n## Guidelines\n- Follow existing project conventions\n- Write tests for new functionality\n- Run tests locally before declaring success\n```\n\n**`.cloche/prompts/fix.md`** — Instructions for fixing failures:\n```markdown\nThe previous attempt had failures. Review the output logs in .cloche/output/\nand fix the issues.\n\n## Guidelines\n- Read the test/lint output carefully\n- Fix the root cause, not the symptoms\n- Run tests again to verify your fix\n```\n\n**`.cloche/prompts/update-docs.md`** — Instructions for keeping docs in sync:\n```markdown\nReview the CLI source code and update usage documentation to reflect any changes.\n```\n\n### 4. Add overrides (optional)\n\nFiles in `.cloche/overrides/` are copied on top of `/workspace/` in the\ncontainer. Use this for container-specific configuration:\n\n```\n.cloche/overrides/\n  CLAUDE.md              # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (replaces host version)\n```\n\n### 5. Make sure your project builds in the container\n\nThe default Dockerfile generated by `cloche init` uses `ubuntu:24.04` as its\nbase image (configurable via `--image`). If your project needs different\ndependencies, edit `.cloche/Dockerfile`:\n\n```dockerfile\nFROM golang:1.25 AS builder\nWORKDIR /src\nCOPY go.mod go.sum ./\nRUN go mod download\nCOPY . .\nRUN CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -o /cloche-agent ./cmd/cloche-agent\n\nFROM ubuntu:24.04\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y git <your-deps> && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\nRUN npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code\nCOPY --from=builder /cloche-agent /usr/local/bin/cloche-agent\nRUN useradd -m -s /bin/bash agent\nWORKDIR /workspace\nRUN chown agent:agent /workspace\nUSER agent\n```\n\nKey requirements for the image:\n- `cloche-agent` binary at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`\n- `git` installed (for pushing results back)\n- An `agent` user (cloche wraps the command with `chown` + `su agent`)\n- `/workspace` as the working directory\n- Your project's build dependencies\n\nThe daemon automatically rebuilds the image when `.cloche/Dockerfile` changes\n(see `cloche run` above). To build manually:\n```\ndocker build -t my-project-agent -f .cloche/Dockerfile .\nCLOCHE_IMAGE=my-project-agent:latest bin/cloched\n```\n\n### 6. Run it\n\n```\ncd my-project\ncloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add feature X\"\n```\n\n## Writing Workflows\n\nWorkflow files use the `.cloche` extension and live in the `.cloche/` directory. See\n[workflows.md](workflows.md) for full DSL reference.\n\n### Step Types\n\n**Agent steps** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent autonomously:\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n**Script steps** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command:\n\n```\nstep test {\n  run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\n### Wiring\n\nConnect steps with `step:result -> next_step`:\n\n```\nimplement:success -> test\nimplement:fail -> abort\ntest:success -> done\ntest:fail -> fix\n```\n\n`done` and `abort` are built-in terminals for success and failure.\n\n### Retry Loops\n\nWire failures back to earlier steps:\n\n```\ntest:fail -> fix\nfix:success -> test    // retry the test\nfix:fail -> abort\n```\n\n### Max Attempts\n\nLimit retries on agent steps. When exhausted, the step returns `give-up`:\n\n```\nstep fix {\n  prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n  max_attempts = \"2\"\n  results = [success, fail, give-up]\n}\n```\n\n### Parallel Branches\n\nWire one result to multiple targets for concurrent execution:\n\n```\ntest:success -> lint\ntest:success -> quality\n```\n\n### Collect (Join)\n\nSynchronize parallel branches:\n\n```\ncollect all(lint:success, quality:success) -> done\n```\n\n`all` fires when every condition is met. `any` fires when at least one is.\n\n### Agent Command Override\n\nAgent steps use Claude Code by default. Override per-step:\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = \"...\"\n  agent_command = \"aider\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\nOr at the workflow level via a `container` block:\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  container {\n    agent_command = \"gemini\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nOr globally via `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` environment variable.\n\nPriority (highest to lowest): step-level `agent_command`, workflow-level\n`container { agent_command }`, `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var, default (`claude`).\n\n### Agent Fallback Chains\n\nUse a comma-separated list in `agent_command` to configure fallback chains. If\nthe first agent errors without reporting a result, the system tries the next:\n\n```\nstep implement {\n  prompt = \"...\"\n  agent_command = \"claude,gemini,codex\"\n  results = [success, fail]\n}\n```\n\nFallback rules:\n- **Command not found or failed to start** — fall back to next command\n- **Exit non-zero without `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — fall back to next command\n- **Exit non-zero with `CLOCHE_RESULT` marker** — use that result (no fallback)\n- **Exit 0** — use result (no fallback)\n- **All commands fail to start** — step returns an error\n- **Last command crashes without marker** — step returns `fail`\n\nKnown agents have default arguments (e.g., Claude gets\n`-p --output-format text --dangerously-skip-permissions`). Other agents receive\nthe prompt on stdin with no extra flags. Override with `agent_args` at the step\nor workflow level.\n\n## Result Protocol\n\nSteps report results by writing a marker to stdout:\n\n```\nCLOCHE_RESULT:<name>\n```\n\nFor script steps, if no marker is written, the exit code determines the result:\n0 = `success`, non-zero = `fail`. Agent steps follow the same convention.\n\n## Prompt Assembly\n\nWhen an agent step runs, Cloche assembles a prompt from multiple sources:\n\n1. The step's `prompt` content (inline or from `file()`)\n2. The user prompt from `.cloche/<run-id>/prompt.txt` (set via `--prompt`)\n3. Validation output from `.cloche/<run-id>/output/*.log` (output from previous script steps)\n4. Result selection instructions listing the step's declared results\n\n## Project Directory Layout\n\n```\nmy-project/\n├── .cloche/\n│   ├── develop.cloche        # Workflow definition\n│   ├── Dockerfile            # Container image\n│   ├── prompts/\n│   │   ├── implement.md      # Prompt templates\n│   │   ├── fix.md\n│   │   └── update-docs.md\n│   ├── overrides/            # Files copied on top of /workspace/ in container\n│   │   └── CLAUDE.md         # Container-specific CLAUDE.md (optional)\n│   └── <run-id>/             # Runtime state (gitignored)\n│       ├── prompt.txt        # User prompt (from --prompt flag)\n│       ├── output/\n│       │   ├── full.log      # Unified chronological log (status + script + LLM)\n│       │   ├── test.log      # Per-step script output\n│       │   └── llm-impl.log  # Per-step LLM conversation output\n│       ├── attempt_count/\n│       │   └── fix           # Retry counter for max_attempts\n│       └── history.log       # Step execution log\n├── src/                      # Existing project source (untouched)\n├── CLAUDE.md                 # Host CLAUDE.md\n└── .git/\n```\n\n## Daemon Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_LISTEN` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Listen address (unix socket or TCP) |\n| `CLOCHE_DB` | `cloche.db` | SQLite database path |\n| `CLOCHE_RUNTIME` | `docker` | `docker` (container) or `local` (subprocess, for dev) |\n| `CLOCHE_IMAGE` | `cloche-agent:latest` | Default Docker image |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | — | HTTP address for the web dashboard. Not started unless set. |\n| `CLOCHE_AGENT_PATH` | (auto-detected) | Path to `cloche-agent` binary (local runtime) |\n| `CLOCHE_LLM_COMMAND` | — | Command for LLM calls — evolution and merge conflict resolution (e.g. `claude`) |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | — | Passed into Docker containers |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_MOUNTS` | — | Extra bind mounts (comma-separated `host:container`) |\n| `CLOCHE_EXTRA_ENV` | — | Extra env vars (comma-separated `KEY=VALUE`) |\n\n### Client Configuration\n\n| Variable | Default | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_ADDR` | `unix:///tmp/cloche.sock` | Daemon address (gRPC) |\n| `CLOCHE_HTTP` | `localhost:8080` | Daemon HTTP address (web dashboard, `cloche logs --follow`) |\n\n## Build Commands\n\n```\nmake build          # Build all binaries to bin/\nmake test           # Run all tests\nmake test-short     # Run tests (skip slow ones)\nmake lint           # Run go vet\nmake proto          #